\begin{abstract}
Automated glaucoma screening models trained on Western fundus datasets are widely assumed to degrade substantially on Indian retinal images due to phenotypic (pigmentation) and acquisition-induced domain shifts. Unsupervised Test-Time Adaptation (TTA) has emerged as a promising paradigm to mitigate such shifts without requiring target-domain labels. In this paper, we conduct a rigorous empircal investigation into the efficacy of Source-Free Domain Adaptation for cross-ethnic glaucoma screening. Using a DINOv3 ViT-Large foundation model, we train a source model on the European AIROGS dataset ($n{=}9{,}540$) and adapt it to the Indian Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u dataset ($n{=}1{,}345$). Our findings fundamentally challenge prevailing assumptions. First, we demonstrate that the DINOv3 source model inherently achieves exceptional zero-shot cross-ethnic generalisation (AUROC: 0.852), performing equivalently to an in-domain supervised Oracle model (AUROC: 0.892). Second, we reveal a catastrophic failure mode in unsupervised adaptation: applying state-of-the-art Information Maximisation objectives causes severe algorithmic collapse (AUROC: 0.390, Specificity: 1\%). Despite introducing targeted corrections---class-prior regularisation and selective entropy minimisation---the model exploits demographic confounders, driving predictions degenerately toward the minority class. We formally characterise this vulnerability, concluding that unsupervised test-time calibration is currently unsafe for deploying foundation models across ethnic shifts in medical imaging.
\end{abstract}

