\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Glaucoma is the second leading cause of irreversible blindness worldwide \cite{tham2014global}. While deep-learning models for automated screening have shown high efficacy within controlled datasets \cite{li2018efficacy}, shifting these models across international demographics introduces a major bottleneck: \emph{cross-ethnic domain shift}. Models trained predominantly on European cohorts, such as AIROGS \cite{vermeer2024airogs}, historically suffer degradation when applied to South Asian retinas, such as those in the Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u dataset \cite{kumar2023chakshu}. 

This degradation stems from phenotypic variations, such as increased melanin pigmentation resulting in darker fundus appearances, interwoven with hardware differences across hospital environments \cite{rajesh2025rps}. Due to global privacy restrictions (e.g., GDPR), source training data cannot typically be transferred to the deployment site. Furthermore, securing local ground-truth labels requires expensive expert ophthalmologist annotations. Consequently, \emph{Source-Free Domain Adaptation} (SFDA), which adapts a pre-trained model solely using unlabelled target data, has gained massive traction as a theoretical panacea.

In this study, we subject SFDA paradigms to rigorous scrutiny in a realistic cross-ethnic glaucoma screening scenario. We utilise DINOv3, a state-of-the-art visual foundation model, to establish a high-capacity baseline. We hypothesised that while zero-shot application of the European model would struggle in India, targeted SFDA (minimising prediction entropy while maximising batch diversity) would recalibrate the feature space and recover performance.

Our empirical findings invert this hypothesis entirely:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{High Zero-Shot Generalisation:} Foundation models (DINOv3) generalise cross-ethnically far more robustly than previously documented CNNs. The zero-shot model achieved a 0.852 AUROC on Indian data, rivalling even the supervised \emph{Oracle} model (0.892).
    \item \textbf{The TTA Collapse:} Unsupervised Test-Time Adaptation induces catastrophic representational collapse. Adaptation methodologies destroyed the robust zero-shot decision boundary, plummeting the AUROC to 0.390 and forcing 100\% sensitivity at the cost of 1\% specificity.
    \item \textbf{Confounder Exploitation:} Even when regularised with exact target-domain prevalence priors (class-prior KL divergence), the unlabelled optimisation conflates pathogenic and demographic features. It learns \emph{how many} cases should be glaucoma, but completely forgets \emph{which ones} they are.
\end{enumerate}

These findings expose a critical vulnerability: deploying unsupervised test-time adaptation on foundation models for cross-ethnic clinical applications is fundamentally unsafe.

