\section{Methodology}
\label{sec:methods}

\subsection{Datasets}
We construct a large-scale, cross-ethnic adaptation benchmark:
\textbf{Source Domain (Europe):} The AIROGS dataset comprises high-resolution, standardised colour fundus images collected across the Netherlands \cite{vermeer2024airogs}. We sampled $n{=}9{,}540$ images, rigorously class-balanced (50\% Referable Glaucoma, 50\% Normal), to train the source model independent of class-imbalance biases.
\textbf{Target Domain (India):} The Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u dataset \cite{kumar2023chakshu} consists of images captured using handheld, non-mydriatic cameras (Remidio, Forus, Bosch) across rural Indian clinics. The dataset is highly imbalanced, reflecting true clinical prevalence (approximately 15\% Glaucoma). We utilise 1,009 unlabelled images for adaptation and 336 strictly held-out images for evaluation.

\subsection{Source Training and the Oracle}
We employed a DINOv3 ViT-Large backbone (16-patch, 303M parameters). To preserve self-supervised textual/structural knowledge, the backbone was largely frozen; only the final two transformer blocks and the dense classification head were fine-tuned via Cross-Entropy loss. 

To determine the ceiling performance for the target domain, we trained an \emph{Oracle} model directly on the fully-labelled Ch\'{a}k\c{s}u training set (using WeightedRandomSampler to handle the 1:6 Glaucoma-to-Normal imbalance).

\subsection{Unsupervised Test-Time Adaptation}
We implemented a standard Source-Free Domain Adaptation workflow, referred to as \emph{Netra-Adapt}, heavily relying on Information Maximisation (IM). The standard IM objective consists of two components:
1. \textbf{Entropy Minimisation ($\mathcal{L}_{ent}$):} Forces the model to output highly confident predictions on the unlabelled target samples point-wise.
2. \textbf{Diversity Maximisation ($\mathcal{L}_{div}$):} Maximises the entropy of the mean batch predictions to prevent degenerate solutions (e.g., predicting all images as normal).

However, during initial experiments, standard IM caused massive mode collapse, grouping all samples into "Normal." To counter this, we designed three advanced corrections meant to stabilise adaptation:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Prior Matching ($\mathcal{L}_{balance}$):} Instead of uniform diversity, we enforced a KL divergence penalty to match the global mean output strictly to the Indian clinical prior of $[0.85, 0.15]$ (Normal:Glaucoma).
    \item \textbf{Selective Entropy:} $\mathcal{L}_{ent}$ was applied exclusively to uncertain samples to prevent feature destruction in already-confident alignments.
    \item \textbf{Removal of Hard Pseudo-labels:} Hard semantic loss was removed to prevent confirmation bias on noisy predictions.
\end{itemize}

