\subsection{The Catastrophic Failure of Adaptation}
As visually demonstrated in Figure \ref{fig:tsne} and \ref{fig:attention_maps}, despite implementing "best practice" regularisations, the SFDA phase yielded an AUROC of 0.390 (worse than random guessing). The model collapsed to predicting Glaucoma for almost every image (Specificity 1\%, Sensitivity 100\%).

This collapse demonstrates a fatal flaw in applying entropy-minimisation principles to clinical data with demographic shifts. When the loss forces the unlabelled target embeddings to satisfy the $[0.85, 0.15]$ prior, the model does not learn pathology. Instead, it co-opts the most salient target-domain features—such as device lighting artefacts or patient melanin levels—and clusters them arbitrarily to satisfy the numerical KL-divergence constraint. The clinical decision boundary learned on European data is functionally obliterated in pursuit of mathematical diversity.

