\section{Discussion and Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

The pursuit of algorithmic fairness and global equity in medical AI has heavily favored unsupervised domain adaptation as a scalable mechanism. However, our results indicate that \emph{the illusion of calibration} is real: models can successfully match target statistical priors while completely forgetting the pathogenic signal. 

We draw two crucial conclusions for the future of cross-ethnic glaucoma screening:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Massive source training beats limited target tuning.} For high-capacity visual foundation models, a massive, diverse out-of-domain dataset (AIROGS) provides more clinical utility than fine-tuning on a small but perfectly representative target dataset.
    \item \textbf{Unsupervised TTA is currently disjoint from medical safety.} Algorithms designed to align unlabelled feature distributions cannot distinguish between a "shift in camera lighting" and a "shift in disease severity." Until adaptation paradigms can formally decouple phenotypic from pathogenic features, Test-Time Adaptation should not be deployed clinically without human-in-the-loop labels.
\end{enumerate}

Future work must abandon pure entropy-based objectives for medical shifts and instead explore structurally-constrained adaptation, multi-modal alignments, or few-shot supervised techniques to safely democratise foundation models in ophthalmology.

